---HEADER---
file:                  tooling/common.py
language:              python
role:                  Shared filesystem and parsing helpers for the
                       tooling/ package: file iteration, project-root
                       walk-up, header-field reading, and date parsing.
                       Cross-cutting result dataclasses (Finding, Report)
                       live in tooling/types.py instead.
layer:                 core
status:                verified
confidence:            high (rationale: authored fresh in this rc and
                       reviewed against design)
generation-pass:       false
read-reason:           task-driven
last-verified:         v0.3-rc6-2026-05-04
maintained-by:         llm
exports:
  - ISLAND_SUFFIX
  - MAINLAND_NAME
  - is_example_path
  - iter_islands
  - source_for_island
  - find_project_root
  - read_header_field
  - parse_last_verified
imports:
  - datetime    :: date
  - pathlib     :: Path
  - re
  - typing      :: Iterable
depends-on:
  - tooling/stale.py          :: imports iter_islands, source_for_island,
                                  read_header_field, parse_last_verified,
                                  is_example_path
  - tooling/spec_router.py    :: imports find_project_root
  - (rc7+) tooling/propagation.py, rules.py
                              :: will import find_project_root,
                                  read_header_field, iter_islands
  - (rc8) tooling/validate.py :: will import iter_islands,
                                  source_for_island, parse_last_verified,
                                  is_example_path
translation-boundary:  none
dynamic-boundary:      false

---SYMBOLS---

SYMBOL: ISLAND_SUFFIX
kind:           constant
pure:           true
total:          true
latency-budget: N/A
effects:
  reads:    none
  mutates:  none
  allocs:   none
  throws:   never
  async:    false
  io:       none
called-by:
  - iter_islands       :: glob pattern
  - source_for_island  :: suffix strip
calls:
  - none
expects:
  - none
runtime-dependencies:
  - none
tests:
  unit:       none — string literal
  regression: none
  security:   none
business-rule: N/A
fragility:    low
fragility-note: N/A

SYMBOL: MAINLAND_NAME
kind:           constant
pure:           true
total:          true
latency-budget: N/A
effects:
  reads:    none
  mutates:  none
  allocs:   none
  throws:   never
  async:    false
  io:       none
called-by:
  - find_project_root  :: file existence check during walk-up
calls:
  - none
expects:
  - none
runtime-dependencies:
  - none
tests:
  unit:       none — string literal
  regression: none
  security:   none
business-rule: N/A
fragility:    low
fragility-note: N/A

SYMBOL: is_example_path
kind:           function
pure:           true
total:          true
latency-budget: <1ms
effects:
  reads:    Path.parts of the input
  mutates:  none
  allocs:   none meaningful
  throws:   never
  async:    false
  io:       none
called-by:
  - iter_islands       :: gates whether to yield
  - rc6+ subcommands   :: gates severity (warning vs error on missing source)
calls:
  - Path.parts (attribute access)
expects:
  - argument is a pathlib.Path
runtime-dependencies:
  - none
tests:
  unit:       none yet
  regression: none yet
  security:   none
business-rule: N/A
fragility:    low
fragility-note: N/A

SYMBOL: iter_islands
kind:           function
pure:           false (filesystem walk; result depends on disk state)
total:          true
latency-budget: O(N) where N = files under root; typically <100ms
effects:
  reads:    filesystem (rglob)
  mutates:  none
  allocs:   yields Path objects lazily
  throws:   propagates OSError on inaccessible directories
  async:    false
  io:       filesystem (directory listing)
called-by:
  - rc6+ subcommands   :: every command that scans islands
calls:
  - Path.rglob :: recursive glob
  - is_example_path :: filter
expects:
  - root exists; if not, rglob yields nothing without erroring
runtime-dependencies:
  - none
tests:
  unit:       none yet
  regression: none yet
  security:   none
business-rule: N/A
fragility:    medium (rationale: filesystem walk on large monorepos
                                  can be slow; no caching here)
fragility-note: rc6+ subcommands call this on every invocation. On very
                large repos, consider materializing the list once at
                the orchestrator and threading it down.

SYMBOL: source_for_island
kind:           function
pure:           true
total:          true
latency-budget: <1ms
effects:
  reads:    none (string manipulation only)
  mutates:  none
  allocs:   one Path
  throws:   never
  async:    false
  io:       none
called-by:
  - tooling/stale.py   ::locate source for mtime check
  - rc8 validate.py    :: cross-check HEADER.file vs companion source
calls:
  - Path.with_name
expects:
  - input path ends in ISLAND_SUFFIX
runtime-dependencies:
  - none
tests:
  unit:       none yet
  regression: none yet
  security:   none
business-rule: N/A
fragility:    low
fragility-note: N/A

SYMBOL: find_project_root
kind:           function
pure:           false (filesystem checks)
total:          true (walks up at most until filesystem root)
latency-budget: O(depth) stat calls; typically <10ms
effects:
  reads:    filesystem (file existence checks)
  mutates:  none
  allocs:   Path objects
  throws:   propagates OSError on permission errors
  async:    false
  io:       filesystem read
called-by:
  - rc7 propagation.py :: locate .llmpropstts at the right level
calls:
  - Path.resolve
  - Path.exists
expects:
  - start is a pathlib.Path
runtime-dependencies:
  - none
tests:
  unit:       none yet
  regression: none yet
  security:   none
business-rule: N/A
fragility:    low
fragility-note: N/A

SYMBOL: read_header_field
kind:           function
pure:           false (filesystem read)
total:          true (bounded by file line count)
latency-budget: <50ms for typical island
effects:
  reads:    filesystem (one file)
  mutates:  none
  allocs:   one string per line read
  throws:   never (catches OSError -> returns None)
  async:    false
  io:       filesystem read
called-by:
  - tooling/stale.py   ::read last-verified, status
  - tooling/stale.py   :: cmd_check_decay -read confidence-review-due
  - rc8 validate.py    :: read various fields
calls:
  - Path.read_text
  - str.splitlines, str.strip, str.startswith
expects:
  - path is a pathlib.Path; non-existence returns None gracefully
runtime-dependencies:
  - none
tests:
  unit:       none yet
  regression: none yet
  security:   none
business-rule: N/A
fragility:    medium (rationale: returns first match only — wrong if
                                  the same key appears nested under a
                                  different parent; fine for HEADER
                                  fields because they are top-level)
fragility-note: only safe for top-level HEADER fields. Nested fields
                like effects.io need section-aware parsing and belong
                in validate.py (rc8). This helper is intentionally
                shallow to prevent subcommand modules from quietly
                assuming nested-field correctness.

SYMBOL: parse_last_verified
kind:           function
pure:           true
total:          true
latency-budget: <1ms
effects:
  reads:    none
  mutates:  none
  allocs:   one date object on success
  throws:   never (returns None on failure)
  async:    false
  io:       none
called-by:
  - tooling/stale.py   ::source-mtime comparison
  - tooling/stale.py   :: cmd_check_decay -due-date comparison
  - rc8 validate.py    :: enforce parseable date when status: verified
calls:
  - re.search          :: pattern match on YYYY-MM-DD
  - date.fromisoformat :: parse
expects:
  - input is a string or None
runtime-dependencies:
  - none
tests:
  unit:       none yet — high priority for first test pass
  regression: none yet
  security:   none
business-rule: N/A
fragility:    medium (rationale: regex-based date extraction; takes
                                  the first YYYY-MM-DD found; pathological
                                  inputs fail gracefully but are not
                                  covered by tests yet)
fragility-note: takes the FIRST YYYY-MM-DD substring it finds. Versions
                like "v0.3-rc1-2026-04-27" parse correctly. Inputs like
                "v3-2024-2025" produce None via isoformat failure.
                Pathological cases not exercised; first test pass should
                cover them.

---RISKS---

security:                none
regression-sensitivity:
  - changing ISLAND_SUFFIX or MAINLAND_NAME breaks every subcommand
  - parse_last_verified regex changes can silently miss valid dates;
    cover with tests before changing
platform-sensitivity:
  - filesystem case sensitivity differs (Windows is case-insensitive,
    POSIX is case-sensitive); rglob "*.llmisland" still matches both
config-dependencies: none

---MEMORY---

ACTIVE-CONSTRAINTS:
  - id: AC-001
    constraint:  every helper here MUST work with stdlib only
    established: 2026-05-03
    evidence:    contract zero-dependency in mainland

  - id: AC-002
    constraint:  read_header_field stays shallow (top-level HEADER
                 fields only). Nested-field parsing belongs in
                 validate.py (rc8), not here.
    established: 2026-05-03
    evidence:    HD-001 below

HISTORICAL-DECISIONS:
  - id: HD-001
    decision:  read_header_field is intentionally shallow
    reason:    deeper parsing (effects.io, tests.unit) requires
               section-aware logic that belongs in validate.py.
               Keeping the helper shallow prevents subcommand
               modules from quietly assuming nested-field
               correctness.
    date:      2026-05-03
    outcome:   stable
    evidence:  inferred-from-design

  - id: HD-002
    decision:  parse_last_verified takes first YYYY-MM-DD found
    reason:    accepts both "v7-2024-03-15" and bare "2024-03-15".
               Pathological inputs ("v3-2024-2025") fail at
               isoformat parsing -> None -> caller treats as "no
               usable date". Acceptable for now; needs tests.
    date:      2026-05-03
    outcome:   stable; tests pending
    evidence:  inferred-from-design

  - id: HD-003
    decision:  pull Finding and Report dataclasses out into
               tooling/types.py
    reason:    initial common.py island hit 417 lines, over the
               file-size red line (400). With 10 exports, even a
               disciplined SYMBOLS section pushed the metadata over
               the limit. Splitting the source by concern (filesystem
               + parsing helpers stay; result types move) brought
               both files comfortably under the limit and made the
               organization more honest — the dataclasses are a
               distinct kind of artifact from the helpers.
    date:      2026-05-03
    outcome:   common.py shrank from 134 → 113 LOC and its island
               from 417 → ~340 lines; types.py is ~40 LOC with a
               ~90-line island
    evidence:  inferred-from-design (file-size-rule pressure)

SUPERSEDED:
  - id: SD-001
    was:            common.py exported Finding and Report alongside
                    filesystem and parsing helpers
    replaced-by:    tooling/types.py (Finding, Report);
                    common.py keeps the file-system and parsing helpers
    superseded-date: 2026-05-03
    keep-because:   explains why callers should import from
                    tooling.types, not tooling.common, even though the
                    earlier rc5 design placed them together
